  "texts": [
    "Fig. 2) and the frame of reference in which eyetracking data are recorded and analyzed.",
    "Some research questions require eye movements to be recorded from freely moving participants (Rodrigues, Vickers, & Williams, 2002).",
    "In such cases, the eye tracker can be mounted on the head of the participant, and data are recorded relative to the head.",
    "In many video-based eye trackers, data are recorded as 3-D gaze vectors or 2-D gaze coordinates relative to the eye tracker's eye-, and/or scene cameras.",
    "If only eye movements are of interest, irrespective of what content participants look at, the eye tracker data can be analyzed directly."
  ],
